posts.com:
People with borderline personality disorder may experience intense mood swings and feel uncertainty about how they see themselves. Their feelings for others can change quickly, and swing from extreme closeness to extreme dislike. These changing feelings can lead to unstable relationships and emotional pain.

People with borderline personality disorder also tend to view things in extremes, such as all good or all bad. Their interests and values can change quickly, and they may act impulsively or recklessly.

Other signs or symptoms may include:

Efforts to avoid real or perceived abandonment, such as plunging headfirst into relationships—or ending them just as quickly.
A pattern of intense and unstable relationships with family, friends, and loved ones.
A distorted and unstable self-image or sense of self.
Impulsive and often dangerous behaviors, such as spending sprees, unsafe sex, substance abuse, reckless driving, and binge eating. Please note: If these behaviors happen mostly during times of elevated mood or energy, they may be symptoms of a mood disorder and not borderline personality disorder.
Self-harming behavior, such as cutting.
Recurring thoughts of suicidal behaviors or threats.
Intense and highly variable moods, with episodes lasting from a few hours to a few days.
Chronic feelings of emptiness.
Inappropriate, intense anger or problems controlling anger.
Feelings of dissociation, such as feeling cut off from oneself, observing oneself from outside one’s body, or feelings of unreality.

Not everyone with borderline personality disorder may experience all of these symptoms. The severity, frequency, and duration of symptoms depend on the person and their illness.

>>10515567
If you divide a number by zero, you should get zero. Any given number is not-nothing, and zero is nothing, and there is no nothing in not-nothing, otherwise not-nothing would be nothing and not not-nothing. Further, there is no nothing in something, but the absence of something (or some thing, in the general) in something could more accurately be characterized as the nothing of that thing, since it's not there to be (something, that is). Further, when you really think about it, as a nothing of that thing, that nothing is arbitrarily attached to the thing in our particular case, so you can't responsibly ascribe the nothing to that thing, as it's simply nothing. Since nothing has no recognized bounds, limitations, or units of measurement, it is infinite, thus there is infinite nothings in all instantiations of somethings, infinite somethings really (including somethings that are presently nothings to accommodate the future tense). As there are infinite nothings in infinite finite somethings, and nothing, again, is characterized by the infinite continuation of the absence of something (alternatively, just not-nothing), all somethings are in actuality, by definition, nothings, so there is no defensible differentiation that can drawn between nothing and something. They are one and the same.

Try to teach yourself something you think would be rewarding and useful. If you feel totally lost, try throwing yourself into something as a newbie. Lots of professional communities will want to help you succeed within them, I'm thinking of outdoor education in particular here. If you keep trying and failing, support like 'neetbux' is an option, but I think a career can really provide the direction and structure that people need in their lives, especially if your work is contributing to equity in your own life and business instead of some cunt boss. Don't ever take a job that won't help you develop in some way, like working in a wareouse or restaurant (if you avoid these jobs if possible you help people in the industries too by creating more demand for workers, if enough people do it). Probably a lot depends on where you live and stuff too. But yeah working for myself is the best thing I did for my mental health as an adult, though it took years of working for somebody else to build those skills. Good luck anon :)

posts.com:
I have genital herpes in the vaginal area.
It's literally a non-issue.

I freaked out at first because I was scared that my (very new) boyfriend was gonna dump me. But I'm not a slimy, cowardly piece of shit, so I bit the bullet and told him immediately. I basically told him what it meant, apologised for the bad news, encouraged him to get tested, and told him "this is a permanent thing, so I understand if you're no longer interested in dating me."
He must have been interested, because he tested negative, then he stuck around for the next 3 years.

At first I was paranoid about having sex because I didn't want him to catch it, and I always felt a little guilty afterwards. For the first few weeks, I always double-checked that he really WANTED to have sex, before proceeding. I didn't do this verbally every time lol, but I'd sort of pull away and let him lead. If he was enthusiastic about it, I took it for consent and acceptance of the risk. When he didn't get sick, I stopped being paranoid, though I did make him get yearly blood tests, just for my own peace of mind. During that entire relationship, he never caught it. Lucky bastard was one of the few people who are immune to that shit.

In 10 years, I have never had another outbreak. I haven't even had an ITCH.
Herpes is only really an issue if you're dating an immunocompromised person, because it can fuck them up. But for the majority of people, you get one shitty outbreak, then you're fine.

IME, people don't really judge you for it. I haven't dated since that last guy, but a few male friends have hit on me at some point in time, knowing damn well that I've got herpes. So obviously people aren't bothered by it.

Some people will of course reject you for it. But as long as you're cool about it, and informative and respectful, most people will be willing to date you.
You're ok, man. Don't stress. Trust me - it's not the death sentence you think it is.
